    "markdown_debrief": "### \ud83e\ude7a Surgical Board Practice Item\n\n**Metadata:** HPB Surgery | Hepatic Anatomy & Resections | Brisbane 2000 Terminology\n**Target Level:** Resident / Attending\n\n**\ud83d\udcdd The Clinical Vignette**\nA 54-year-old woman with a history of colon cancer presents with two synchronous liver metastases. Preoperative triphasic CT of the abdomen demonstrates a 3 cm lesion in segment VI and a 2 cm lesion in segment VII. The multidisciplinary tumor board recommends a parenchymal-sparing anatomic resection of these segments. \n\nAccording to the Brisbane 2000 Terminology of Liver Anatomy and Resections, which of the following statements is true regarding this planned procedure and hepatic nomenclature?\n\n* A) Right anterior sectorectomy corresponds to resection of segments VI and VII\n* B) Extended right hepatectomy corresponds to resection of right hemiliver and left lateral sector\n* C) Right posterior sectorectomy corresponds to resection of segments VI and VII\n* D) Extended left hepatectomy corresponds to resection of left hemiliver and segment IV\n\n**Correct Answer:** C) Right posterior sectorectomy corresponds to resection of segments VI and VII\n\n---\n\n### \u26a1 SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**\ud83d\udccc S \u2013 Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n* **The Verdict:** Correct: C. Right posterior sectorectomy corresponds to resection of segments VI and VII.\n* **The Diagnostic Pivot:** The identification of Couinaud segments VI and VII as the constituents of the **right posterior sector** (or section), while segments V and VIII constitute the **right anterior sector**. \n\n**\ud83c\udfaf H \u2013 Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n* **Surgical Mechanism:** The Brisbane 2000 terminology was established by the Scientific Committee of the International Hepato-Pancreato-Biliary Association (IHPBA) to standardize hepatic anatomy and resections. It is based on first-, second-, and third-order vascular and biliary branching patterns. The right portal vein branches into the right anterior sector branch (supplying V and VIII) and the right posterior sector branch (supplying VI and VII).\n* **Clinical Execution:** Anatomic parenchymal-sparing resections (such as a right posterior sectorectomy) optimize the future liver remnant (FLR) volume, reducing the risk of post-hepatectomy liver failure (PHLF) while achieving oncologically sound R0 margins.\n* **\ud83d\udc41\ufe0f Mental Operative Theatre:** During a right posterior sectorectomy, the surgeon mobilizes the right liver, identifies the right hepatic vein (which runs in the right portal fissure and serves as the deep anatomical boundary separating the anterior and posterior sectors), and divides the right posterior portal pedicle. Ischemic demarcation on the liver surface then clearly outlines the boundaries of segments VI and VII.\n\n**\u274c A \u2013 Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n* **Option A (Incorrect):** Right anterior sectorectomy corresponds to the resection of segments **V and VIII** (not VI and VII). This is a common point of confusion on board exams.\n* **Option B (Incorrect):** An extended right hepatectomy (right trisectionectomy) corresponds to the resection of the right hemiliver (segments V, VI, VII, VIII) plus the **left medial section** (segment IV), leaving only the left lateral section (segments II and III) as the FLR. Resecting the left lateral sector (II and III) instead would leave only segment IV, which is anatomically non-viable due to vascular isolation.\n* **Option D (Incorrect):** An extended left hepatectomy (left trisectionectomy) corresponds to the resection of the left hemiliver (segments II, III, IV) plus the **right anterior section** (segments V and VIII), leaving only the right posterior section (segments VI and VII) as the FLR. Segment IV is already a standard component of a left hemiliver.\n\n**\ud83d\udcca R \u2013 Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n* **Conceptual Overview:** Derived from the IHPBA Brisbane 2000 Terminology guidelines for liver resections.\n\n| Brisbane 2000 Term | Alternative Term | Segments Resected | Anatomical Boundary / Landmark |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Right Hemiehepatectomy** | Right Hepatectomy | V, VI, VII, VIII (+/- I) | Cantlie's Line (Middle Hepatic Vein) |\n| **Left Hemiehepatectomy** | Left Hepatectomy | II, III, IV (+/- I) | Cantlie's Line (Middle Hepatic Vein) |\n| **Right Anterior Sectionectomy** | Right Anterior Sectorectomy | V, VIII | Right Portal Fissure (Right Hepatic Vein) |\n| **Right Posterior Sectionectomy** | Right Posterior Sectorectomy | VI, VII | Right Portal Fissure (Right Hepatic Vein) |\n| **Right Trisectionectomy** | Extended Right Hepatectomy | IV, V, VI, VII, VIII | Left Umbilical Fissure |\n| **Left Trisectionectomy** | Extended Left Hepatectomy | II, III, IV, V, VIII | Right Portal Fissure |\n\n**\u26a0\ufe0f Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n* **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz):** Both textbooks emphasize Couinaud's segments but note that the term \"lobectomy\" is obsolete and should be replaced by \"hepatectomy\" or \"hemiehepatectomy\" per Brisbane 2000.\n* **Society Guidelines (IHPBA):** Strongly discourages the use of \"lobectomy\" and \"extended lobectomy\" because they do not align with true lobar anatomy (which is embryological/biliary, not vascular).\n* **The Discrepancy:** Some older question banks or poorly translated keys may mistakenly swap \"anterior\" and \"posterior\" or use the outdated term \"trisegmentectomy.\" On modern examinations, Brisbane 2000 terminology is the absolute standard.\n\n**\ud83d\udca1 P \u2013 Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n* **The Board Pearl:** *Remember: \"Post-Six-Seven\" (Posterior = VI and VII) and \"Ant-Five-Eight\" (Anterior = V and VIII). Extended right takes IV; extended left takes V and VIII.*"
