    "markdown_debrief": "### \ud83e\ude7a Surgical Board Practice Item\n\n**Metadata:** HPB | Pancreas Transplantation | Donor Selection Criteria\n**Target Level:** Resident / Attending\n\n**\ud83d\udcdd The Clinical Vignette**\nA transplant coordinator is evaluating a 32-year-old deceased donor for potential multiorgan procurement, including the liver, kidneys, and pancreas. The donor has no history of diabetes mellitus or alcohol abuse and died of a traumatic brain injury. On review of the donor's characteristics, which of the following is an established criterion for pancreas donor selection to minimize the risk of post-transplant graft thrombosis and pancreatitis?\n\n* A) Donor body mass index (BMI) < 30 kg/m\u00b2\n* B) Complete absence of a replaced right hepatic artery arising from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA)\n* C) Donor age up to 65 years\n* D) Cold ischemia time of up to 24 hours\n\n**Correct Answer:** A) Donor body mass index (BMI) < 30 kg/m\u00b2\n\n---\n\n### \u26a1 SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n**\ud83d\udccc S \u2013 Set the Stage (The Verdict & Diagnostic Pivot)**\n* **The Verdict:** Correct: A) Donor body mass index (BMI) < 30 kg/m\u00b2.\n* **The Diagnostic Pivot:** The clinical scenario of selecting a deceased donor for pancreas transplantation. The key pivot is identifying the donor-specific risk factors that correlate with early graft loss. Donor obesity (BMI $\\ge$ 30 kg/m\u00b2) is a powerful predictor of graft pancreatitis, focal necrosis, and subsequent graft thrombosis.\n\n**\ud83c\udfaf H \u2013 Highlight Excellence (The Surgical \"Why\" & Pathology)**\n* **Surgical Mechanism:** The pancreas is highly sensitive to ischemia-reperfusion injury and mechanical manipulation. In obese donors (BMI > 30 kg/m\u00b2), the pancreas is often infiltrated with fat (steatosis/lipomatosis), making it soft, friable, and prone to microvascular compromise, parenchymal necrosis, and subsequent graft thrombosis or severe post-reperfusion pancreatitis.\n* **Clinical Execution:** Selecting a donor with a BMI < 30 kg/m\u00b2 (ideally < 28 kg/m\u00b2) and age < 50 years optimizes graft microperfusion and minimizes the risk of early technical graft loss, which is most commonly caused by graft thrombosis (splenic vein or portal vein thrombosis).\n* **\ud83d\udc41\ufe0f Mental Operative Theatre:** During procurement, the surgeon inspects the pancreas. A suitable pancreas graft appears firm, lobulated, and pale pinkish-yellow without significant fatty infiltration. An unsuitable obese graft appears yellowish, greasy, soft, and lacks distinct lobulation, often tearing easily during mobilization.\n\n**\u274c A \u2013 Address the Gaps (Systematic Distractor Demolition)**\n* **Option B (Incorrect):** A replaced right hepatic artery (rRHA) arising from the SMA is a common anatomical variant (found in ~15-20% of cases). It is **not** a contraindication to pancreas procurement. The procurement surgeon can safely reconstruct the rRHA using an iliac artery Y-graft (reconstructing both the splenic and superior mesenteric arteries of the pancreas graft while preserving the rRHA for the liver graft) or by sharing the arterial supply between the liver and pancreas teams.\n* **Option C (Incorrect):** While kidneys and livers can be procured from older donors (expanded criteria donors), the pancreas is highly sensitive to donor age. The ideal donor age is 10 to 40 years, with an upper limit of 50 to 55 years. Donors > 55-60 years have a significantly higher rate of graft failure, atherosclerosis of the donor splenic/SMA vessels, and poor endocrine function.\n* **Option D (Incorrect):** The pancreas is highly intolerant to prolonged cold ischemia. While kidneys can tolerate up to 24\u201336 hours of cold ischemia, the maximum acceptable cold ischemia time for a pancreas graft is 12 hours (ideally < 10 hours) to prevent severe ischemia-reperfusion injury and graft thrombosis.\n\n**\ud83d\udcca R \u2013 Review Learning Points (Evidence-Based Framework)**\n* **Conceptual Overview:** Pancreas donor selection criteria are designed to minimize technical graft loss (thrombosis, pancreatitis, anastomotic leak), which remains the leading cause of early graft failure. (Reference: *Sabiston Textbook of Surgery*, Chapter on Transplantation).\n\n| Pancreas Donor Criterion | Ideal Threshold / Finding | Clinical / Surgical Rationale | Key Guideline / Consensus |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Donor Age** | 10 to 50 years | Avoids age-related atherosclerosis and poor beta-cell reserve | UNOS / OPTN Guidelines |\n| **Donor BMI** | < 30 kg/m\u00b2 (ideally < 28) | Minimizes fatty infiltration, graft pancreatitis, and thrombosis | UNOS / OPTN Guidelines |\n| **Cold Ischemia Time** | < 12 hours (ideally < 10) | Prevents severe ischemia-reperfusion injury and graft loss | IPTR (International Pancreas Transplant Registry) |\n| **Arterial Anatomy** | Replaced RHA is acceptable | Requires bench reconstruction (Y-graft) but is not a contraindication | ASTS / Surgical Consensus |\n\n**\u26a0\ufe0f Critical Guideline Updates & Textbook Conflicts**\n* **Standard Textbooks (Sabiston / Schwartz):** Emphasize strict donor selection criteria, including age < 50 years and BMI < 30 kg/m\u00b2 to avoid graft thrombosis.\n* **Society Guidelines (OPTN/UNOS):** While these are the \"ideal\" criteria, some centers selectively use \"marginal\" donors (e.g., BMI up to 32 kg/m\u00b2 or age up to 55) for highly sensitized recipients or in combination with machine perfusion trials, but BMI > 30 remains a major risk factor.\n* **The Discrepancy:** In clinical practice, a replaced right hepatic artery is frequently encountered and managed with bench reconstruction, whereas board exams often test this to ensure candidates know it is *not* a contraindication.\n\n**\ud83d\udca1 P \u2013 Plan for Improvement (The Exam Heuristic)**\n* **The Board Pearl:** If evaluating a pancreas donor, remember that **BMI < 30 kg/m\u00b2 and age < 50 years** are the hard physiological limits to prevent graft thrombosis, while **anatomical variants (like a replaced right hepatic artery) are NOT contraindications** and can be reconstructed."
